i) What is main()?

   main() is also a function. It's a special function because it's where every C program starts executing.

   Think of it like this:

   Computer
       │
       ▼
   Starts execution
       │
       ▼
   main()

   The operating system calls main(), and from there, your program runs.

ii) Think of main() as the manager

Imagine a company.

main() is the manager.
Other functions are employees.

The manager doesn't do every task personally.

Instead, it assigns work:

main()
│
├── readInput()
├── calculate()
├── displayResult()
└── saveData()

This makes the program easier to understand and maintain.

2) /* Standard library functions in C */

Library functions are pre-written functions provided by the C Standard Library. Instead of writing common tasks yourself, you can simply call these functions.
Think of them as ready-made tools.

For example, if you want to print something on the screen, you don't write the code that communicates with the operating system. You simply use:

printf("Hello");

Here, printf() is a library function.

/* Why do we need library functions? */

Imagine you want to:

Print output
Read input
Find the length of a string
Calculate a square root
Open a file
Generate a random number

You could write all of these yourself, but it would take a lot of time.

Instead, C provides these functions in its standard library.

Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    printf("Hello World");

    return 0;
}

You wrote only:

printf("Hello World");

but the actual implementation of printf() contains thousands of lines of code written by the library developers.


/* Where do library functions come from? */

They are declared in header files.

For example,

#include <stdio.h>

makes functions like

printf()
scanf()
getchar()
putchar()

available.



/* Common Header Files */

i) <stdio.h>      --> standard input output

Used for input and output.

Functions:

printf()
scanf()
getchar()
putchar()
fopen()
fclose()

Example

#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    printf("Hello");
}


ii) <math.h>

Used for mathematical operations.

Functions:

sqrt()
pow()
sin()
cos()
log()
ceil()
floor()

Example

#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>

int main()
{
    printf("%.2f", sqrt(25));

    return 0;
}

Output

5.00

iii) <string.h>

Used for string manipulation.

Functions:

strlen()
strcpy()
strcat()
strcmp()
memcpy()

Example

#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

int main()
{
    char name[] = "ChatGPT";

    printf("%lu", strlen(name));

    return 0;
}

Output
7


iv) <stdlib.h>

Used for utilities like memory allocation and conversions.

Functions:

malloc()
calloc()
free()
rand()
atoi()
exit()

Example

#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main()
{
    printf("%d", rand());

    return 0;
}


v) <ctype.h>

Used for character handling.

Functions:

toupper()
tolower()
isdigit()
isalpha()

Example

#include <stdio.h>
#include <ctype.h>

int main()
{
    printf("%c", toupper('a'));

    return 0;
}

Output
A


/* User-defined function vs Library functions */

i) Library Function: Already written for you.

printf("Hello");

You only use it.

ii) User-defined Function: You write it yourself.

#include <stdio.h>

void greet()
{
    printf("Hello");
}

int main()
{
    greet();
}